A. Super Classs Definition¶

import numpy as np
from abc import ABC, abstractmethod

# Super class for machine learning models 

class BaseModel(ABC):
    """ Super class for ITCS Machine Learning Class"""
    
    @abstractmethod
    def train(self, X, T):
        pass

    @abstractmethod
    def use(self, X):
        pass

    

class Classifier(BaseModel):
    """
        Abstract class for classification 
        
        Attributes
        ==========
        meanX       ndarray
                    mean of inputs (from standardization)
        stdX        ndarray
                    standard deviation of inputs (standardization)
    """

    def __init__(self, ):
        self.meanX = None
        self.stdX = None

    def normalize(self, X):
        """ standardize the input X """
        
        if not isinstance(X, np.ndarray):
            X = np.asanyarray(X)

        self.meanX = np.mean(X, 0)
        self.stdX = np.std(X, 0)

        # TODO: Finish this normalization
        Xs = (X - self.meanX)/self.stdX
        return Xs

    def _check_matrix(self, mat, name):
        if len(mat.shape) != 2:
            raise ValueError(''.join(["Wrong matrix ", name]))
        
    # add a basis
    def add_ones(self, X):
        """
            add a column basis to X input matrix
        """
        self._check_matrix(X, 'X')
        return np.hstack((np.ones((X.shape[0], 1)), X))

    ####################################################
    #### abstract funcitons ############################
    @abstractmethod
    def train(self, X, T):
        pass
    
    @abstractmethod
    def use(self, X):
        pass

B. Pocket Algorithm¶

Pocket Learning Algorithm keeps the best result seen so far in its pocket. The best result means the number of misclassification is minimum. If the new weights produce a smaller number of misclassification than the weights in the pocket, then replace the weights in the pocket to the new weights; if the new weights are not better than the one in the pocket, keep the one in the pocket and discard the new weights. At the end of the training iteration, the algorithm returns the solution in the pocket, rather than the last solution.

Implementation Strategy:

  • Initialize the pocket weight vector, w_pocket to 0 and use this weight vector as the initialized weight vector W0
  • For each training iteration, perform the following steps
    • Run the training step of perceptron learning algorithm and obtain the updated weight vector
    • Evaluate the above weight by compaing the number of misclassification on the entire sample set with the number of misclassification performed by w_pocket
    • If the weight of the current iteration is better then replace w_pocket with the new weight
  • Return the final w_pocket and terminate the session
In [28]:
from copy import deepcopy as copy 


class PocketAlgo(Classifier):
    maxiter = 1000
    alpha = 0.1
    
    def __init__(self, alpha, maxiter):
        Classifier.__init__(self)
        self.alpha = alpha
        self.maxiter = maxiter

    # return 1 if w is better -1 if wp is better
    def compare(self, X, T, w, wp):
        y = np.sign(X @ w)
        yp = np.sign(X @ wp)
        return 1 if np.sum(y == T) >= np.sum(yp == T) else -1

    def train(self, X, T):
        w = np.zeros(3)
        w_pocket = copy(w)
        X1 = self.add_ones(X)
        N = X.shape[0]
        for i in range(self.maxiter):
            converged = True
            for k in range(N):
                y = w @ X1[k]
                if np.sign(y) != np.sign(T[k]):
                    w += self.alpha * T[k] * X1[k]
                    converged = False
                    if self.compare(X1, T, w, w_pocket) > 0: 
                        w_pocket[:] = w[:]
            if converged:
                print("converged at ", i)
                return w_pocket
                break
        return w_pocket

    def use(self, X, w_pocket):
        X1 = self.add_ones(X)
        return X1@w_pocket

C. QDA¶

Discriminant analysis is used to determine which variables discriminate between two or more naturally occurring groups.

QDA (Quadratic Discriminant Analysis) is closely related to linear discriminant analysis (LDA), where it is assumed that the measurements are normally distributed. Unlike LDA however, in QDA there is no assumption that the covariance of each of the classes is identical. To estimate the parameters required in quadratic discrimination more computation and data is required than in the case of linear discrimination. If there is not a great difference in the group covariance matrices, then the latter will perform as well as quadratic discrimination. Quadratic Discrimination is the general form of Bayesian discrimination.

Implementation Strategy

-Input values are normalised using their mean and standard deviation

-The normalised values are then passed to the QDA function which applies the following formula to the data. k(x)=0.5ln|k|0.5(xk)1k(xk)+lnP(T=k)

-The output is two different quadratic boundary functions which help us plot the decision boundary, by leveraging the contour function.

In [29]:
def QDA(X, mu, sigma, prior):
    sigma_inv = np.linalg.inv(sigma)
    diffv = X - mu
    return -0.5  * np.log(np.linalg.det(sigma)) \
            - 0.5 * np.sum(diffv @ sigma_inv * diffv, axis=1) \
            + np.log(prior)

D. LDA¶

LDA (Linear Discriminant Analysis) tries to find the linear combination of features which best separates two or more classes of examples. The resulting combination is then used as a linear classifier. LDA has a dependent variable that is categorical (i.e. the class label). LDA is also closely related to principal component analysis (PCA) and factor analysis in that both look for linear combinations of variables which best explain the data. LDA explicitly attempts to model the difference between the classes of data. PCA on the other hand does not take into account any difference in class.

Implementation Strategy

-Input variables are normalised using mean and standard deviation.

-The normalised values are passed to the LDA function which applies the following formula to the data.

$$ \delta_k(\XV) = \XV^\top \boldsymbol\Sigma^{-1} \boldsymbol\mu_k -\frac{1}{2} \boldsymbol\mu_k^\top \boldsymbol\Sigma^{-1}\boldsymbol\mu_k + \ln P(T = k). $$

-The output is two different quadratic boundary functions which help us plot the decision boundary, by leveraging the contour function.

Ref: https://docs.rapidminer.com/latest/studio/operators/modeling/predictive/discriminant_analysis/linear_discriminant_analysis.html

In [31]:
def LDA(X, mu, sigma, prior):
    sigma_inv = np.linalg.inv(sigma)
    return np.sum((X @ sigma_inv) * mu \
                - 0.5 * (mu @ sigma_inv) * mu, axis=1) \
                + np.log(prior)

E. Logistic Regression¶

Logisitc regression works on the principle that given a series of inputs, it is able to categorize the output into one of two possible categories (0 and 1). Logisitc regression still uses the basic formula for Linear Regression with one exception, Logisitc regression applies a sigmoid function. The sigmoid function can be defined as

g = 1 / (1 + exp(-z))

To generate probabilities, logistic regression uses a function that gives outputs between 0 and 1 for all values of input X. There are many functions that meet this description, but the used in this case is the logistic function.

One of the parameters that is used by Logisitc Regression is called the loss function. A loss function works by picking random values or weights and find how the algorithm performs against those weights. The function is shown in detail in the implementation.

The goal of Logisitc regression is to minimise loss function by adjusting the above weights. The solution is by calculating the derivative of the loss function with respect to each weight

In [33]:
def scattermethod( X, Y, N=200):
    g1 = (0.6 + 0.6 * np.random.rand(N), np.random.rand(N))
    g2 = (0.4+0.3 * np.random.rand(N), 0.5*np.random.rand(N))

    data = (g1, g2)
    colors = ("red", "blue")
    groups = ("<50K", ">50K")

    # Create plot
    fig = plt.figure()
    ax = fig.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)

    for data, color, group in zip(data, colors, groups):
        x, y = data
        ax.scatter(x, y, alpha=0.8, c=color, edgecolors='none', s=30, label=group)

    plt.title('Matplot scatter plot')
    plt.legend(loc=2)
    plt.show()

class LogisticRegression:
    def __init__(self, lr=0.01, num_iter=100000, fit_intercept=True, verbose=False):
        self.lr = lr
        self.num_iter = num_iter
        self.fit_intercept = fit_intercept
        self.verbose = verbose
    
    def __add_intercept(self, X):
        intercept = np.ones((X.shape[0], 1))
        return np.concatenate((intercept, X), axis=1)
    
    def __sigmoid(self, z):
        return 1 / (1 + np.exp(-z))
    def __loss(self, h, y):
        return (-y * np.log(h) - (1 - y) * np.log(1 - h)).mean()
    
    def fit(self, X, y):
        if self.fit_intercept:
            X = self.__add_intercept(X)
        
        # weights initialization
        self.theta = np.zeros(X.shape[1])
        
        for i in range(self.num_iter):
            z = np.dot(X, self.theta)
            h = self.__sigmoid(z)
            gradient = np.dot(X.T, (h - y)) / y.size
            self.theta -= self.lr * gradient
            
            z = np.dot(X, self.theta)
            h = self.__sigmoid(z)
            loss = self.__loss(h, y)
                
            if(self.verbose ==True and i % 10000 == 0):
                print(f'loss: {loss} \t')
    
    def predict_prob(self, X):
        if self.fit_intercept:
            X = self.__add_intercept(X)
    
        return self.__sigmoid(np.dot(X, self.theta))
    
    def predict(self, X):
        return self.predict_prob(X).round()

Discussion about evaluation metrics¶

To test how well our models are performing, I will using the evaluation paramater of accuracy. Accuracy of model is tested by running the predictions of the model against the test data we split into 80:20 paritions. By comparing the test results against the predictions and calculating the percentage score, we can determine how many predictions our model actually got right. The formula for calculating the score is as follows:

score = 0 if score == prediction: increase score by 1 accuracy = ((score/total number of samples)) * 100

def normalize(X):
    """ standardize the input X """

    if not isinstance(X, np.ndarray):
        X = np.asanyarray(X)

    meanX = np.mean(X, 0)
    stdX = np.std(X, 0)

    # TODO: Finish this normalization
    Xs = (X - meanX)/stdX
    return Xs

Discussions about classificaion model comparison¶

Based on the analysis done on the data above using the 4 different classification algorithms, we can draw the following conclusions: The algorithms perform differently for different datasets. However, based on the current dataset, pocket algorithm gives the highest accuracy but takes a long time to process the data. Logistic Regression in comparison take a short amount of time and produces good accuracy. However based on the current dataset, logisitc regression deosn't seem to be performing well. These techniques work well on a smaller dataset. However, when dealing with a larger dataset, showing the data visually can be very challenging. It is also very cumbersome to study each pair of data to see how it affects the target variable. This is now similar to how an unsupervised learning algorithm works.

Linear Discriminate Analysis (LDA) and Quadratic Discriminate Analysis (QDA) can be used in this case. When the dimensionality is high, we apply say LDA to our data, and by this we take into consideration different possible relations to our data using the different matrix operations like covariance and mean. Alongside the scatter matrices, these give a good idea about the data using the following eigenvalue and its corresponding eigenvector. We take the highest eigenvalue, and we notice that when the eigenvalue is high enough, the more information about the data that we have. In LDA, we convert the larger dimension data set into a linear dimension we have to identify the best possible features using the above-mentioned process and thereby get the best possible results. This wont work very well when the data which cannot be easily linearly separable or even for smaller clearly visible data sets, for which logistic regression with sigmoid function could be the best solution for.

Logistic regression is the best on smaller datasets with clear linear separation. It takes in input the learning rate and iterations, and with a smaller data set a large number of iterations can be leveraged to get better results as this helps in being able to best fit the data. There is however concern of overfitting if the wrong features and the wrong model to execute is chosen for this process. A good accuracy in our case was obtained in the case of logistic regression as well.
